  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How can I be sure people won't steal my idea during a pitch?",
  "response": "Protecting your idea during a pitch is an important concern. Here are some steps you can take to minimize the risk of theft:\n\n1. **Non-Disclosure Agreements (NDAs):**\n   Consider asking attendees to sign an NDA before presenting your idea. An NDA legally binds them not to disclose or use the information without your permission.\n\n2. **Do Not Over-Share:**\n   Avoid sharing every detail about your idea. Focus on the high-level concept and the value it offers rather than the specifics of how it works.\n\n3. **Patent Protection:**\n   If possible, secure a patent for your idea before pitching it. A provisional patent can be a quicker way to obtain initial protection.\n\n4. **Trademarks and Copyrights:**\n   Register any trademarks or copyrights that might apply to your idea. This helps establish your ownership and give you a basis for legal action if someone tries to steal it.\n\n5. **Document Everything:**\n   Keep detailed records of your work, including drafts, emails, and notes. These can serve as evidence of your ownership if disputes arise later.\n\n6. **Vet Your Audience:**\n   Be selective about who you pitch to. Choose reputable investors, collaborators, or potential clients who have a history of integrity.\n\n7. **Establish a Paper Trail:**\n   Send follow-up emails summarizing your pitch and including the date you shared your idea. This documentation can serve as proof you disclosed the idea to them.\n\n8. **Build a Strong Brand:**\n   Work on building your brand and presence. If people associate your idea with your name, it becomes harder for others to steal and claim it as their own.\n\n9. **Legal Consultation:**\n   Consult with a lawyer who specializes in intellectual property. They can offer more tailored advice and ensure you're taking all necessary precautions.\n\n10. **Leverage First-Mover Advantage:**\n   The faster you can execute and bring your idea to market, the harder it will be for others to capitalize on it.\n\nWhile no method offers complete protection, combining several of the above strategies will provide significant safeguard against potential theft.",
